irst major systematic treatise in the medieval West against various homosexual acts, provides a critique of Peter Damian’s arguments, and outlines his life. The annotated translation is followed by a translation of the letter of Pope Leo IX in reply to Damian’s Treatise, an extensive bibliography, and indexes. The book will be of interest to students of medieval history and religion, to ethicists and students of social mores, and to persons generally concerned with the historical roots of present-day attitudes to homosexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay clergy. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  abible and homosexuality.  abiblical understanding of homosexuality.  achristian and gay.  aclerics.  agay priests.  agomorrah.  ahomosexuality.  algbtq and religion.  amedieval.  apriests.  aqueer priests.  areligious and gay.1 aPayer, Pierre J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920842140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208421/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles